CSS specificity determines which styles win when multiple rules target the same element. Understanding it saves hours of debugging.
## The Scoring System
Specificity is calculated as a three-part score: **(A, B, C)**
- **A** — ID selectors (`#header`)
- **B** — Class selectors (`.card`), attribute selectors (`[type="text"]`), pseudo-classes (`:hover`)
- **C** — Element selectors (`div`), pseudo-elements (`::before`)
```css
/* (0, 0, 1) */
p { color: black; }

/* (0, 1, 0) */
.text { color: blue; }

/* (0, 1, 1) */
p.text { color: green; }

/* (1, 0, 0) */
#main { color: red; }

/* (1, 1, 1) */
#main p.text { color: purple; }
```
Higher specificity always wins. Within the same specificity, the last rule wins.
## :where() and :is()
These pseudo-classes take a selector list, but differ in specificity:
```css
/* :is() takes the highest specificity of its arguments */
:is(#header, .nav) a { } /* specificity: (1, 0, 1) */

/* :where() always has zero specificity */
:where(#header, .nav) a { } /* specificity: (0, 0, 1) */
```
`:where()` is perfect for writing default styles that are easy to override:
```css
/* Easy to override — zero specificity from :where() */
:where(.card) {
  padding: 1rem;
  border-radius: 8px;
}

/* Any class selector overrides the above */
.featured-card {
  padding: 2rem;
}
```
## Cascade Layers
CSS `@layer` gives you explicit control over which groups of styles take priority:
```css
@layer base, components, utilities;

@layer base {
  a { color: blue; }
}

@layer components {
  .nav a { color: white; }
}

@layer utilities {
  .text-red { color: red; }
}
```
Later layers always beat earlier layers, regardless of specificity. This means a simple `.text-red` in the utilities layer beats `#main .nav a.link` in the components layer.
---
The modern specificity toolkit: use `:where()` for easily-overridable defaults, `:is()` for concise selectors, and `@layer` for architectural control over your stylesheet.
